We intend to use the GHPM model to replicate resurgent epidemics, like influenza or COVID-19 (see Fig. 1), so that we adopt a SIR epidemic model with relapse43, also know as a SIRI model44. Hence, we make the following assumptions:
Each individual can be in one of three mutually exclusive states (susceptible S, infected I, or recovered R), where the fraction of the population in each state, at any discrete moment in time t, is denoted as S(t), I(t), and R(t), respectively. At every time step, an infected coming in contact with a susceptible individual, can transfer the disease with a probability \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\lambda$$\end{document}λ. Subsequently, an infected individual can recover with a probability \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu$$\end{document}μ, after which he remains recovered, but only for a specific period (see “GHPM experimental setup” for details on the reproduction number estimation). After this timeout period, the individual becomes susceptible again.
Homogeneous population mixing is sufficiently accurate at the small granularity of households30,34, as well as for short duration (1 day) in higher administrative divisions (e.g., block, neighborhood). Moreover, we consider that epidemic contagion only occurs between infected and susceptible individuals found in the same administrative division at the same time t. Given \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
